add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipd">The Arts/Cultural Desk Review </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">The Arts/Cultural Desk; SECTC</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">That Porn Addict May Be an Actor</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>The man with the grizzled beard first saw bare breasts in a family copy of National Geographic. The woman with frizzy blond hair was taken to her first pornographic movie by a date. He turned out to be the star. The man in the blue shirt likes gay porn even though he's straight, mostly. The woman in the red shirt likes it, too. ''I'm horrified by some of the stuff I watch,'' she says.</Para><Para>These people were speaking on Monday night at ''Prurience,'' a self-help program for people addicted to pornography that is also a tricky, mutable, overstuffed performance piece by the British conceptualist Christopher Green, co-directed by Holly Race Roughan.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Part immersion, part indictment and part encounter group, it guides the crowd through a set program of conflict and disclosure, mixing unscripted audience comments and more carefully composed revelations from actors. (That woman in the red shirt was one of them.) Go ahead and guess which were more revealing.</Para><Para>''Prurience'' is part of the Guggenheim's Works &amp; Process series and on Monday, the Wright restaurant had been reappropriated as a meet-up space, the coffee counter cluttered with pens and name tags, a plate of cookies and several urns bubbling with hot water for tea. (Was milk for that tea too triggering?)</Para><Para>As Mr. Green skittered inside, his red braid dangling out of a ''Prurience''-branded baseball cap, a bulging Ikea bag hefted over his shoulder, audience members were encouraged to take seats, write expectations for the evening on scraps of paper and mix unawares with the actors in the crowd.</Para><Para>One audience member read a statement for the evening; others read those expectations: ''To release myself from guilt,'' ''To have a good time,'' ''To see some skin.'' That last one? Didn't happen, though there was some spontaneous hugging. We did all sing the ''Prurience'' song -- ''I am the one in control'' -- and write our own verse by committee: ''I am confused and shy/Yet titillated/By lascivious trepidation.'' Yeah, it needs work.</Para><Para>We raised our hands when asked if we had ever felt lonely, if we had ever wished for an easier life. We watched a corporate video. Mr. Green, adopting an American accent as Chris, the soft-voiced facilitator, asked for volunteers to share their first experiences with porn. We listened to longer speeches and shorter speeches and heard a terrible poem. Then, in accidentally-on-purpose style, the evening devolved.</Para><Para>''Prurience'' is at once an immersive mingling of theater and reality, a satire of 12-step culture, an exploration of group dynamics and an investigation into whether sex addiction is an addiction at all or just a marketing construct and a convenient way for men accused of sexual assault to hide out for a while. That's a few too many forms and subjects.</Para><Para>Yes, it's embarrassing to find yourself in a well-lit room discussing intimate subjects with tea-sipping strangers. I blush easily and I blushed often. But I'd argue that this is a productive discomfort. There's plenty of shame that accompanies the consumption of pornography and if books and articles and podcasts are any indication, plenty of anxiety about the ways in which free streaming content is changing us sexually and socially.</Para><Para>So it felt usefully uncomfortable to listen to real people sharing their own stories and a lot more comfortable and less useful to hear actors recite monologues. (For the most part, the actors are pretty easy to spot. Their performances are more emphatic, their lines less spontaneous.) The actors' content was more extreme -- borderline prurient -- but the form was a lot safer, the messaging obvious.</Para><Para>There was enough theater just in watching Chris lead the group and watching the audience try to configure itself into a group that could be led. Most of the best moments came from Chris's candid interactions with the spectators, his up-talking manipulations and barbed sympathy.</Para><Para>In a recent New York Times interview, Mr. Green said that he set out to make ''the least theatrical thing ever.'' He's not there yet. A more daring piece might have explored compulsion and control and, yes, lascivious trepidation, without using actors at all.</Para><Para>Prurience</Para><Para>Through March 31 at the Wright restaurant at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum; guggenheim.org. 1 hour 50 minutes.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By ALEXIS SOLOSKI </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Christopher Green, in baseball cap, leading actors and audience members in ''Prurience,'' a play at the Wright restaurant in the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum. (PHOTOGRAPH BY ROBERT ALTMAN) </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

